* Namecheck project: IsAvailable is inflexible

`http.DefaultClient` (a convenient [[https://pkg.go.dev/net/http#Client][`*http.Client`]] [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singleton_pattern][_singleton_]]) is a hard-coded dependency of the current version of our `IsAvailable` function:

  func IsAvailable(username string) (bool, error) {
    // ...
    res, err := http.DefaultClient.Do(req)
    // ...
  }

However, the possibility to specify (or "inject") a custom HTTP client is desirable, especially for configuring request timeouts or [[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cAWlv2SeQus&t=1554s][satisfying a cloud provider's constraints]].

How should we redesign `IsAvailable` to achieve such flexibility? Any ideas?



* Methods are great for dependency injection

Reducing methods to functions coated in syntactic sugar is tempting, but you would be overlooking their power! Whatever dependencies the method needs can indeed conveniently be [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependency_injection]["injected"]] ahead of time in its receiver.

Heureka! The `IsAvailable` function can be turned into a method on some `GitHub` struct type with a field of type `*http.Client`:

  type GitHub struct {
    Client *http.Client
  }

  func (gh *GitHub) IsAvailable(username string) (bool, error) {
    // ...
    res, err := gh.Client.Do(req)
    // ...
  }



* Methods are great for dependency injection (cont'd)

When instantiating the `GitHub` type, users are now free to "inject" the client of their choice, either [[https://pkg.go.dev/net/http#NoBody][`http.DefaultClient`]] or some custom instance of [[https://pkg.go.dev/net/http#Client][`*http.Client`]]:

  gh := github.GitHub{
    Client: &http.Client{
      Timeout: 5 * time.Second,
    },
  }
  avail, err := gh.IsAvailable("jub0bs")
  // ...

